ncontrolled electrical activity in the brain","Prolonged post-event confusion","Maintained consciousness with weakness","Gradual onset over several minutes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESyncope is defined as a transient loss of consciousness (TLOC) due to temporary global cerebral hypoperfusion, characterized by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERapid onset\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShort duration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpontaneous and complete recovery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA key feature is \u003Cstrong\u003Eloss of postural tone\u003C/strong\u003E, often leading to a fall, followed by a quick and full recovery of baseline neurological function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncontrolled electrical activity in the brain\u003C/strong\u003E characterises seizures, not syncope\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged post-event confusion\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of seizures; syncope patients usually recover clarity quickly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintained consciousness with weakness\u003C/strong\u003E suggests other conditions like stroke or vertigo\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradual onset over several minutes\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon in syncope, which typically has a rapid onset\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe loss of postural tone in syncope is a protective mechanism that places the person in a horizontal position, helping to restore cerebral blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Syncope is a transient loss of consciousness due to global cerebral hypoperfusion.","Loss of postural tone is a characteristic feature of syncope that distinguishes it from other causes of loss of consciousness.","Unlike seizures, syncope does not involve abnormal electrical activity in the brain."],"references":["Runser LA, Gauer RL, Houser A. Syncope: Evaluation and Differential Diagnosis. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Mar 1;95(5):303-312. PMID: 28290647","Grossman SA, Badireddy M. Syncope. 2023 Jun 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28723035","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16352"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T07:01:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T07:02:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9043"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71112"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"